snippet.textDisplay:
In short, no.

The longer answer is that there are multiple threads to this issue woven together with the theme of hypocrisy:

1) The CPS prosecuting 'vulnerable' people. The CPS does this literally every day; most people didn't care at all until someone off the telly couldn't handle it. There are probably hundreds if not thousands of suicides in the last decade linked to accusations of crime and it only becomes an issue now because a pretty woman has fallen victim. We can't expect the criminal justice system to grind to a halt because the accused may harm themselves as a result of facing consequences for their alleged actions.

2) The media - whenever a celebrity is faced with criminal allegations the tabloids are going to have a feeding frenzy, particularly if it relates to an in vougue issue such as domestic violence. However what drives this is the insatial desire of the public for gossip and scandle involving celebs; the very same public who now point the finger at the press who's websites they visited and newspapers they bought for the latest development in Ms Flack's situation.

3) Domestic violence (DV) - this is a sensitive and complex issue but one over which there is much hypocrisy. Women are generally more likely to be the victims of DV than men, but it does not mean that men don't suffer from DV. Experts believe that men are less likely to report DV than women and DV overall is underreported. It is estimated that at least 1/3 of DV victims are male and that many of the other 2/3 of cases involve an element of mutuality (often involving alcohol). Women who perpetrate DV are more likely to use a weapon than a man, they are also more likely to launch 'surprise attacks' such as when the victim is sleeping. Victims of DV often attempt to withdraw their allegations for various reasons.

In the context of increasing awareness of DV, and particularly increasing acknowledgement of male victimhood in DV cases (and more laws passed to prevent DV such as the recent coersive relationships law) is it any surprise that the CPS chose to continue their prosecution? They had the evidence and it is certainly in the public interest to do so.

4) Gender 'equality' - while as a society it appears that we want men and women to be treated as equals on an individual level we seem to want to still hold onto the privileges and stereotypes of gender when it suits us.

To conclude, while I'm sorry that she felt like she had to take her own life, I have little sympathy with Ms Flack's role in the circumstances that led to her tragic act. At the end of the day it appears that she conducted a vicious and sustained assault using a potentially deadly weapon upon an unsuspecting victim. She ought to have faced the consequences for this as anyone else should and would be expected to.

In my opinion, it appears that Ms Flack was someone who has spent their life mostly insulated from the negative consequences of her actions and unfortunately when she actually had to face the music she was unable to handle it - because she hadn't had to deal with negative consequences as much as the average person, she was unable to develop appropriate coping strategies for when things went wrong. However, this is mostly not actually her fault (it takes others to excuse people from their bad actions) which is why we want to label her as a victim despite being directly responsible for the circumstances that led to her suicide.

We'll all sigh and say "oh dear", we'll find a scapegoat to blame and wash our hands of it and salve our souls, but we won't learn any lessons unfortunately (See also Grenfell).
